This paper is likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and computer vision (cs.CV) sub-categories, as it proposes a new approach to training generative adversarial networks (GANs) that improves the stability and quality of generated data samples. It also involves the use of discriminators to estimate the probability of real and fake data, which is a common technique in GANs and falls under the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the optimization of GANs, which is related to the neural networks (cs.NE) sub-category, and presents results on generating high-resolution images, which could be relevant to the graphics (cs.GR) sub-category.
